Syphilitic infection of the stomach is currently rare. Given the protean manifestations of this disease, gastric involvement in secondary or tertiary syphilis remains a diagnostic challenge. Endoscopic examination may show numerous shallow ulcerations with surrounding erythema, or a nodular mucosa with enlarged, thickened folds, suggestive of adenocarcinoma or lymphoma. Microscopic examination reveals severe gastritis with dense plasma cell infiltrates and varying numbers of neutrophils and lymphocytes. Gland destruction, vasculitis with endothelialitis, and ill-formed granulomas are seen. Warthin-Starry silver stain or modified Steiner stain may reveal numerous spirochetes. However, in many cases, immunofluorescence studies and PCR are required to establish a definitive diagnosis (Figs. 9-8
and 9-9
).91
